{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478032"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:07:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:07:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14908"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14908"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.67,0.02,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7599"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104505"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7599"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14908"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86832"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1515"},{"type":"tags","id":"3617"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37594"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104505"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her Aunt with a 30-minute history of an itchy rash on her face that developed shortly after eating scrambled eggs for breakfast. She was having her first sleepover at her Aunty\u0027s house, and she has never eaten eggs before as her parents are vegan. Her brother carries an epi-pen for severe peanut allergy. She has a history of eczema but no other medical conditions. She takes no regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she is crying but settles easily with her Aunty, and vital signs within normal limits. There are raised, erythematous, pruritic wheals on her face and neck. She has not vomited or had any diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intramuscular adrenaline","Oral antihistamine","Topical corticosteroid","Oral prednisolone","Intramuscular antihistamine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with localised urticaria following first exposure to eggs. While this suggests a IgE mediated food allergy, the absence of systemic symptoms (respiratory distress, cardiovascular compromise) differentiates this from anaphylaxis and guides appropriate management. With a brother who has an anaphylactic food allergy, and a history of eczema, the family is likely to be atopic. Egg allergy is the second most common food allergy in children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antihistamine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment for acute urticaria without systemic involvement. It will help relieve symptoms and can be safely administered in the primary care setting. The patient should be observed for at least 30 minutes to ensure no progression to systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were signs of anaphylaxis such as respiratory distress, hypotension, or significant facial swelling. These features are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroid\u003C/strong\u003E is not effective for acute urticaria, which is mediated by histamine release. Topical steroids are more appropriate for chronic inflammatory skin conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered for severe or refractory urticaria but is not necessary for mild, localised symptoms that are likely to respond to antihistamines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular antihistamine\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for routine management of urticaria in children. The oral route is preferred as it is less invasive, equally effective for non-emergency situations, and has a better safety profile in the primary care setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing acute management, the patient may be referred for formal allergy testing and provided with interim advice about avoiding eggs. Parents should be educated about the signs of anaphylaxis and when to seek emergency care, as well as a written allergic reaction plan. She should not undergo allergy testing for food that she has not yet consumed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Oral antihistamines are first-line treatment for acute urticaria without systemic symptoms.","Intramuscular adrenaline is reserved for anaphylaxis with respiratory or cardiovascular compromise.","Egg allergy is the second most common food allergy in children and often presents with urticaria on first exposure."],"references":["Food Allergy - IgE mediated food allergy. Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Clinical Guidelines. 2021. https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Food_allergy_-_IgE_mediated_food_allergy/","Caubet JC, Wang J. Current understanding of egg allergy. Pediatr Clin North Am. 2011 Apr;58(2)  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3069662/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86832"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14908"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86832"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T12:25:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T12:26:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7599"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104505"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"ite